[1]
Date: 25 Mar 2004
From: William B. Karesh, DVM <wkaresh@wcs.org> [edited]

ProMED-mail has provided excellent updates as this case (Undiagnosed
deaths, cervids - USA (WY)) unfolded, but the latest comment/possible
recommendation from the moderator requires a very strong caveat.
[From the previous posting :"If Game and Fish believes this to be the
cause, then perhaps they could supply supplement feeding to prevent such
heavy consumption of the lichens and thus prevent the deaths of these
animals. Â­ Mod.TG]
Recommendations for [responding to] a dramatic but rare event, such as
_Parmelia_ toxicosis, need to be evaluated carefully in terms of avoiding
unintended and sometimes insidious consequences. Supplemental feeding of
free-ranging wildlife in North America has been associated with the spread
of infectious diseases such as tuberculosis in deer and brucellosis in
elk. The economic costs of these diseases -- as borne by government
agencies, the livestock industry, and the sporting industry -- have been
huge, not to mention the impact on the species affected and other species
living around them.
Preventing and controlling infectious diseases at the landscape level,
involving thousands of species of animals, plants, and invertebrates across
a matrix of land-use patterns, ownership, and legal authorities, requires
thoroughly analyzed recommendations and well-planned implementation efforts.
As Dr. Bill Weber once said, "It's not rocket science, it's much more
challenging than that."
--
William B. Karesh, D.V.M.
Director Field Veterinary Program
Wildlife Conservation Society
2300 Southern Blvd.
Bronx, NY 10460
U.S.A.
<wkaresh@wcs.org>
